text:
 @dadarkvador24  wider lens means more light gets in during the same period of time.
effectively it lowers the worst lighting conditions in which it can take the same quality image, in this case its like going from needing 100 ISO to only needing 80, so arguably a 20% improvement to low light photo acquisition, how well it will actually impact the results is debatable though and most photos will be taken at far better lighting conditions where it won't help nearly as much.
Get the ultra if you don't care about the money, if you're hesitating, you are probably considering overspending on something you don't need, especially since you didn't know what it is, so you don't need it for your work.
